  <title>Examples</title>

<example xml:id="ex-finding-ethings1">
<statement>
<p>
Find the eigenvalues of the matrix
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  3 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  3
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
For each eigenvalue, find all its eigenvectors, find its eigenspace, and 
give a specific example of an 
eigenvector.
</p>
<p>
The characteristic polynomial is
<md>
<mrow>
\det(A-\lambda I) \amp  = \det\left(
\begin{bmatrix}
    3 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  3
  \end{bmatrix}
-
\begin{bmatrix}
    \lambda \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  \lambda
  \end{bmatrix}
\right)                                         \\
\amp  =
\begin{vmatrix}
  3 - \lambda \amp  1 \\
  1           \amp  3-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
\\
\amp  = (3-\lambda)^2 - 1         \\
\amp  = \lambda^2 - 6\lambda + 8  \\
\amp  =(\lambda - 2)(\lambda -4)
</mrow>
</md>.
So the roots of the characteristic equation <m>\det(A -\lambda I) = 0</m> are <m>\lambda =2</m> and 
<m>\lambda = 4</m>, which means these are the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>.
</p>
<p>
For <m>\lambda = 2</m>, we solve <m>(A-2I)\vect{x} = \vect{0}</m> for <m>\vect{x}</m>. 
Row reducing,
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{c} A-2I \amp  \vect{0}
\end{amatrix}
=
\begin{amatrix}{cc}
  1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 1 \amp  1 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\xrightarrow{R_2 \mapsto R_2 - R_1}
\begin{amatrix}{cc}
  1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</me>.
The solutions are <m>y = t</m>, <m>x = -t</m>, for <m>t \in \R</m>. So the eigenvectors 
for <m>\lambda =2</m> are <m>[-t, t]</m> for <m>t\in \R \setminus \{0\}</m>. For the 
eigenspace, we include <m>\vect{x} = \vect{0}</m>, so we can also include <m>t=0</m> to get <me>
E_2(A) = \left\{\colvec{-t}{t} \; \middle| \; t \in \R\right\}
</me>. Taking <m>t = 1</m>, a specific eigenvector is <m>[-1, 1]</m>.
</p>

<p>
For <m>\lambda =4</m>, we solve <m>(A-4I)\vect{x} = 0</m> for <m>\vect{x}</m>. Row reducing,
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{c} A-2I \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
=
\begin{amatrix}{cc}
  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 1 \amp  -1 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\xrightarrow{R_2 \mapsto R_2 + R_1}
\begin{amatrix}{cc}
  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</me>.
The solutions are <m>y = t, x = t</m>, for <m>t\in \R</m>. So the eigenvectors are 
<m>[t, t]</m> for <m>t \in \R\setminus \{0\}</m>, the eigenspace is <me>
E_4(A) = \left\{\colvec{t}{t} \;\middle|\; t \in \R\right\},
</me> and taking <m>t = 1</m> gives that <m>[1, 1]</m> is an eigenvector.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-finding-ethings2">
<statement>
<p>
Find the eigenvalues of the matrix
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  1  \amp  2  \amp  0 \\
  -1 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \\
  0  \amp  1  \amp  1
\end{bmatrix}

</me>.
For each eigenvalue, find a corresponding eigenvector.
</p>
<p>
The characteristic polynomial is
<md>
<mrow>
\det(A - \lambda I) \amp  =
\begin{vmatrix}
  1-\lambda \amp  2          \amp  0 \\
  -1        \amp  -1-\lambda \amp  1 \\
  0         \amp  1          \amp  1-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
\\
\amp  = (1-\lambda)
\begin{vmatrix}
  -1 - \lambda \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
- 2
\begin{vmatrix}
  -1 \amp  1 \\
  0  \amp  1-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
\\
\amp  = (1-\lambda)[(-1-\lambda)(1-\lambda) - 1] - 2[-(1-\lambda) - 0] \\
\amp  =(1-\lambda)[(-1-\lambda)(1-\lambda)-1 +2]                       \\
\amp  = (1-\lambda)(\lambda^2 -1-1+2)                                  \\
\amp  = \lambda^2 (1-\lambda)
</mrow>
</md>.
So the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>0</m> and <m>1</m>.
</p>

<p>
For <m>\lambda =0</m>, we solve
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{c}
  A - I \amp  \vect{0}
\end{amatrix}
=                                   
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  -1 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  1 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow{R_2 \mapsto R_2 + R_1}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  1 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto R_3 - R_2} 
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<p>
The solutions are <m>z = t, y = -t, x = 2t</m>, for <m>t\in \R</m>. Taking <m>t = 1</m>, <m>[2, -1, 1]</m> 
is an eigenvector for <m>\lambda =0</m>.
</p>

<p>
For <m>\lambda =1</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{c}
  A - I \amp  \vect{0}
\end{amatrix}
=                                                                     
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  0 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  -1 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow{R_1 \leftrightarrow R_2}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -1 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3 \mapsto R_3 - \frac{1}{2}R_2]{R_1 \mapsto R_1 + R_2} 
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -1 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<p>
The solutions are <m>z = t</m>, <m>y = 0</m>, <m>x=t</m>, for <m>t\in \R</m>. Taking <m>t=1</m> 
gives that <m>[1, 0, 1]</m> is an eigenvector for <m>\lambda =1</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

