<p>
If <m>A</m> is a triangular matrix, then because <m>\lambda I</m> is a diagonal matrix, 
<m>A-\lambda I</m> is still triangular. If the diagonal entries of <m>A = [a_{ij}]</m> are <m>a_{ii}</m>, 
then <m>A-\lambda I</m> is a triangular matrix with <m>a_{ii} - \lambda</m> on its diagonal. Since 
the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of its diagonal entries,
<me>
\det(A-\lambda I) = (a_{11} - \lambda)(a_{22} -\lambda) \cdots (a_{nn}-\lambda)
</me>.
Therefore the solutions of the characteristic equation are <m>\lambda = a_{11}, a_{22}, \dots, a_{nn}</m>.
</p>

<assemblage xml:id="evalues-tri-matrices">
<p>
<term>Conclusion:</term> The eigenvalues of a triangular matrix are its diagonal entries.
</p>
</assemblage>

<example xml:id="ex-finding-evalues-tri-matrix">
<statement>
<p>
Find the eigenvalues of the matrix
<me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  5 \amp  2 \amp  4 \\
  0 \amp  3 \amp  1 \\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  -2
\end{bmatrix}

</me>.
</p>

<p>
<m>A</m> is upper triangular, so its eigenvalues are the diagonal entries <m>5</m>, <m>3</m> and <m>-2</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

